  "dateModified": "2026-03-01",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-01",
  "description": "Semantic HTML is the practice of choosing HTML elements based on the meaning they convey rather than the visual appearance they produce. A \u0026lt;nav\u0026gt; element declares that its contents are navigation links; an \u0026lt;article\u0026gt; declares a self-contained piece of content; a \u0026lt;header\u0026gt; marks introductory material. These elements communicate structure to browsers, screen readers, search engines, and any other software that processes the document.\nThe alternative — using generic elements like \u0026lt;div\u0026gt; and \u0026lt;span\u0026gt; for everything and relying on CSS classes for visual differentiation — produces documents that look correct to sighted users but carry no machine-readable structure. Screen readers cannot announce what role a section plays; search engines cannot distinguish primary content from navigation; automated tools cannot extract the document\u0026rsquo;s outline.\n",
  "keywords": "web-design",
  "name": "semantic HTML",
